    # [Scene: New Promenade / Seawall Ribbon-Cutting | Midday]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Triumphant brass overdubbed with an urgent, high-tempo string ostinato]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Reporters' murmurs, camera shutters, a ceremonial scissor-cut amplified over a speaker]
    "You feel the signature you pressed into municipal paper as if it's a physical seam under your skin. The ink has dried, but the pressure hasn't released. You are here because you chose motion—because, in a"
    "greenhouse lit once by seedlings and rain, you folded your throat around a decision that made things move. The seawall is the proof of that movement: precise joints, a promenade glass enough to see your face"
    "in, and a set of concession stands that smell faintly of new varnish and coffee."
    show livia_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    livia_chen "This wall is for every child who should not have to measure the tide to see if their home will be there tomorrow. It's for jobs, for safety, and for the future of New Aster."
    "Her voice is warm and practiced; the crowd answers with measured, relieved applause—some genuine, some performative. Cameras eat the moment like small birds swallowing the last of the light. You watch the room filling with photos of a safer town and feel the air thin."
    "You step closer after the speech, notebook in your hand because habits die slower than towns. The page is blank, and for a beat it is easier to let the page be blank than to name the people who will lose anchorage while the ledger gains columns."
    hide livia_chen

    scene bg ch9_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant honk of a delivery truck, the muffled creak of folding chairs]

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "You heard her. It's—"

    "You" "Steady work,' you repeat, hearing the edges. 'And steady displacement."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "I—"

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "I know what this buys. I know what it costs. I tried to make things that could keep everyone—' His hand gestures, helpless and then emphatic. 'It wasn't enough. The grant money, the contracts—it's bigger than what we could do in the Arbor."
    show mara_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "So what do we have now? A safer map and fewer people on it."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "It's not that simple, Mara.' (He steps closer, voice pitched low, urgent.) 'I can't make something out of nothing. I tried to do right. You know I did."
    "Your throat feels like it's been packed with gravel. You want to tell him you know, and that that knowledge is a poor substitute for the smell of his paint and the way he figured new"
    "bolts out with ragged fingers. You want to tell him you don't know. You say both."

    mara_kestrel "You did what you could, Eli. But the people who could keep living with their boats—some of them are gone. Rafi's boy packed at dawn. Grandma Hira's nephew took the last crate of gear and wept on the pier."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan laughs once, a short thing that doesn't reach his eyes."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "I folded my jumpsuit into someone else's hands this morning. Told them they'd have first crack at my tools. Is that—' (he jerks his chin at the promenades and the plaque) '—enough? Is that redemption? Is that even dignity?"
    "Your hands curl around the notebook until the paper crimps. He looks like he's about to ask you to come with him—to leave with him—but then he chokes on the words and instead sets his duffel down."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "I'm going to try—somewhere else. Maybe the city. Maybe a co-op. I don't know. I can't—' His voice goes small, a child voice under the noise. 'I can't stay and watch my friends priced out."

    mara_kestrel "Eli—"
    "He reaches for your hand; you take it because it's the last honest gesture left between you in this crowd of curated progress. His fingers are callused and still smell faintly of salt and engine oil. He squeezes once, like a promise or an apology."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "I'll write. If I find work that matters, I'll come back and help—we can still—"

    mara_kestrel "We can try."

    menu:
        "Drop everything and follow Eli to the harbor":
            "You make a move to gather his duffel. For a hot second you imagine two of you against the tide. Eli's hand hovers, then steadies your wrist. He shakes his head, the motion furious and ashamed. 'You need to be here,' he says, and you let the duffel fall back into place."
        "Let him go and stay for the press to ask you questions":
            "You let go. The crowd shifts back to the stage bright with flashbulbs. Livia is taking questions; reporters swivel toward you like vultures sensing drama. You step forward instead of to the boats, and something in your chest tightens with the weight of absence."

    # --- merge ---
    "The crowd recedes; Eli turns and walks through the new plaza as if crossing a border. The promenade's glass reflects him small and thin; the sea beyond glitters like a thing concreted over"
    hide mara_kestrel

    scene bg ch9_3be532_3 at full_bg
    "You watch him recede until the crowd and the ceremony reassemble around a different center—the mayor, a ribbon cut into neat arcs—and you feel the scrape of public congratulation like sandpaper along your palms."
    # [Scene: New Promenade / Alleyways Below Promenade | Afternoon]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Faint radio chatter from construction crews, the hollow echo of a jackhammer further down; a child's distant wail]
    "The formal applause fades but the consequences are louder. Rent posting notices, digital displays listing 'AVAILABLE UNITS'—prices that read like a taking. Men with clipboards and tight suits walk by with the air of appraisers; their steps are the sort you can hear even when they're polite."
    "Grandma Hira appears at the edge of the crowd like a memory stepping into a new frame. She smells like lavender and boiled seaweed; her shawl is a map of repairs. Her eyes are bright and terrible."
    show grandma_hira at left:
        zoom 0.7

    grandma_hira "They've made the sea polite, child. They put a fence where we used to argue with it. Who will hum at dawn if they sell the sheds and the boats and replace our voices with places to hang lanterns for visitors?"
    show mara_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "They said—' (you falter) '—they said safety. And jobs."

    grandma_hira "There's a place for jobs. There's a place for safety. There's also a place for remembering how to whittle a rope and mend a sail. When remembering is priced into an exhibit, it becomes novelty."
    "Her voice lands like a pebble thrown into your sternum. It skips and bruises."
    hide grandma_hira
    hide mara_kestrel

    scene bg ch9_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A low, almost inaudible hum as the city's new lighting system powers on; the hum feels, for a moment, like judgment]
    "You walk the new plaza alone later as the crowd thins. Food trucks hum; a band plays cover songs that have lost the teeth of their original anger. The promenade is clean; the rainwater drains into"
    "channels that boast engineering lines in the stone. Plaques with bullet points about 'community benefits' are set like apologies in bronze."
    "A reporter asks you for a quote. You give one that sounds like it belongs to someone who has been schooled in compromise—precise, careful, watchful of legal lines. It reads better on camera than it does in your stomach."
    # [Scene: Private Tent Behind the Dais | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Minimal piano—each note tight as a held breath]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant fade of the crowd; the nearer sound of the seawall's pumps running like a lung]
    "You and Livia are alone for the first time since the applause. The tent smells faintly of coffee and industrial-grade fabric softener. Her eyes are tired in a way you haven't seen; she unfastens one cuff and rubs at it with a thumb."
    show livia_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    livia_chen "Mara. I—' (she stops, recalibrates) 'I know people are hurting. I knew there would be displacement. We proposed relocation assistance. We opened a fund. We—"
    show mara_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "You opened funds. You rezoned. You hired management firms. You called the reports 'development metrics'."

    livia_chen "Yes. Because if we did nothing, New Aster would be—what? Sunk? Stripped of infrastructure? The projections were brutal. The models demanded a scale that our piecemeal projects couldn't satisfy. I did the math, Mara. I did what the town needed on paper."

    mara_kestrel "On paper."
    "Her fingers drum on the table, anxious punctuation."

    livia_chen "I didn't want people to lose homes. I thought, foolishly, that I could shepherd the process. I thought I could make a plan that kept our heritage and brought funding. I misjudged—some of the market effects, some of the speed. There were people I thought we could protect who slipped through the safety net."
    "Her voice breaks like a thin thing. The practiced façade cracks and reveals, briefly, the person behind the platform—a person who took a hard, political route and now sees the human scatter."

    livia_chen "I misjudged the harm. I'm sorry."
    "You stare at the word. The sound of architected sorrow. The admission lands and fractures you."

    mara_kestrel "Sorry for the models?' you ask, and the bitterness cuts. 'Sorry for the policy? Sorry for Rafi's boy sleeping in his truck? Sorry for Eli leaving with no fixed return?"
    "Livia looks down—humiliation or grief, you're not sure. When she raises her eyes again, there's a terrible clarity there."

    livia_chen "I will try to do better where I can. I will press for displacement funds to be real and immediate. I'll—' She searches for a thing big enough to balance losses. 'I will add covenants. I'll change contracts. Tell me where to sign and I will sign."

    mara_kestrel "You helped start the process that priced them out. You offered legal patches now, after the fact. The seawall isn't a neutral tool—it's a lever."

    livia_chen "Tell me how to use the lever without collapsing the market."
    "Her question is not rhetorical; it's hunger in a public form. You could give her a blueprint. You could name the concessions that would actually make a difference: real subsidies, rent control measures, community land trust"
    "covenants. But the very existence of the seawall accelerates capital in ways that contracts can only partially arrest."
    "You feel rage flare and then drown in a more precise grief—the kind that looks like math and policy but smells like empty sheds and packed boats."

    menu:
        "Demand immediate, legally binding covenants and refuse to be placated by promises":
            "You press your palm flat on the folding table, breath coming fast. 'Write it now,' you tell her. Livia's jaw sets; she nods slowly, then reaches for her tablet. It's a start. But as the legal language flows onto the screen, you can feel the slippage—contracts will be litigated, loopholes will eat at goodwill, and the paperwork that promises salvation may arrive too late."
        "Accept her apology and focus on what you can salvage locally":
            "You let out a long, shaky breath and say nothing sharp. 'Okay.' The word folds into your ribs like a bandage. Livia looks relieved. You both step out of the tent and onto the promenade. The work you can still do feels small—and suddenly enormous."

