    hide mara_kestrel

    scene bg ch9_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single high violin note sustains, then warps into a low, aching drone]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant thud of heavy doors—someone is moving out, somewhere below; the scrape of packing crates]
    "You stand in the plaza after the event has packed away its banners and speeches. The crowd is gone. The sculpted wave-bench catches the salt light and throws it back in a way that makes everything"
    "look like a photograph. You flip your notebook open and write the word: 'CURATOR' across the top of the page. The word looks both right and ridiculous."
    "You think of every time you'd chosen inclusion over spectacle, of every single, ragged vote to repair rather than replace. You think of the haunted praise for being 'practical' and 'realistic'—how those words can be used"
    "like knives to shave memory off a town. The seawall stands; its surface is smooth and unblemished. It keeps the metrics low and the insurers calm. It keeps the bigger picture safe in spreadsheets."
    "You breathe in salted air, and it tastes like a bargain half-kept."

    "A message buzzes on your wristband—Eli" "Got to the ferry. Can't talk long. Love you."
    "You fold the notebook closed. It snaps with the small, decisive sound of a life compartmentalized. You have done something that made the town safer in measure and emptier in memory. The cost is an ache that will not be vaccinated by better statistics."
    "You touch the sea-glass pendant at your throat—a child-thing, a talisman—and for a moment the weight of it is the only honest thing you can find. You forgive Livia in a legal sense, because forgiveness is"
    "sometimes a pragmatic tool that lets you keep working. You do not forgive in the soft way that erases loss; that kind of undoing is reserved for storms and stories that we haven't been given."
    "The promenade hums under your feet like a machine that has been wound and now runs on."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A low, sustained chord resolves into silence]
    "You close your notebook and head down the new steps toward the alleys that were rezoned. You will do the work you can—covenants, petitions, community funds, midnight meetings—but you carry the knowledge of what was traded."
    "The town is safer in the way numbers can be safe. It is poorer in the only ways numbers cannot count: the names that walked away, the songs that are slower to be sung, the hands"
    "that no longer know how to splice rope."
    "You pause at the old boardwalk's edge—where the sea used to come up into conversation—and you make yourself a promise you cannot fully keep: to try to stitch the missing parts back, even if you know some things cannot be sewn whole again."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_9 at full_bg
